<DOC><DOCNO> AP891202-0106 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1509EST</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Olympics     12-02 0210</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Summit-Olympics,200</SECOND><HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD><UNK>Bush Asks Soviets To Join In Backing 2004 Olympic Bid for Berlin</UNK><DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush urged Soviet leaderMikhail S. Gorbachev on Saturday to join the United States inproposing that the 2004 Olympics be held in Berlin, a U.S. officialsaid.   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said theOlympic proposal was among the subjects Bush raised on the firstday of his summit talks with Gorbachev. The discussions werescheduled for a Soviet missile cruiser, but moved to the Sovietliner Maxim Gorky because of bad weather.   Berlin as a site for the Olympics was suggested bythen-President Ronald Reagan, at a time when the Berlin Wall _symbol of Europe's division _ seemed to rule out any possibility.Reagan did not propose a date.   The idea of bidding for the 2004 games surged in Germanyimmediately after the East Berlin government's decision Nov. 9 toease travel restrictions on its citizens and to cut new crossingsin the wall, allowing millions of East Germans to visit West Berlinfreely.   Four West German cities preparing to bid for the 2004 summerOlympics immediately said they would drop their applications ifBerlin were to become a candidate.</TEXT></DOC>